/** Art & Drama DIP Tracker 25-26 — seeded from v2.xlsx (grey DIP fields + initial collaborative entries). */
window.DIP_TRACKER_SEED = {"version":1,"schoolYear":"2025-26","sheets":{"gc1m1":{"challenge":"Challenge 1: To provide an inclusive education meeting the needs of all learners","mission":"Mission 1: Improve attendance of a targeted group of young people","commitments":[{"id":"gc1m1-1","commitment":"Early intervention, parental contact via Pastoral Care, and closer tracking for pupils with attendance <75%.","subject":"Both","lead":"S. MacLean / M. Gallacher / K. Nutt / S. Airdrie","successMeasure":"Improved attendance across Art & Drama, especially for ASC and care-experienced pupils.","dataArea":"School-wide attendance audit (Aug–Mar) identified 19% of S2–S6 pupils with attendance <75%. Faculty tracking flagged a parallel pattern in Art & Drama classes, with ASC and care-experienced pupils overrepresented in the low-attender cohort.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Behaviour Interventions (+4 months). Evidence shows that targeted, early-stage interventions combining home contact, restorative conversations and personalised tracking improve engagement for pupils at risk of disengagement. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 3.1 (Ensuring wellbeing, equality and inclusion).","resources":"In-service Day time for staff training on the attendance workflow; Pedagogy Pod focused on engagement strategies; Faculty meeting time to review tracker data; Pastoral Care liaison; SEEMiS attendance reports.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 3.1 – How well are we ensuring wellbeing, equality and inclusion for our most vulnerable learners? To what extent does early intervention and parental contact improve attendance for pupils with <75% attendance, particularly ASC and care-experienced pupils?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Attendance workflow agreed; target pupil list (<75%) created and shared with Pastoral Care; baseline attendance % recorded per pupil.","progress":"Workflow launched in line with Pastoral Care procedures and baselines established for all S2–S6 pupils. Take-up of staff parental contact was slower than hoped at the start of session due to competing priorities; system fully embedded by end of Term 1."},"t2":{"measure":"Weekly attendance monitoring evidenced; first round of parental phone calls completed; tracker shared and discussed with Pastoral Care.","progress":"Weekly monitoring now routine across both subjects. Parental contact made for the majority of target pupils. Early signs of engagement from families but limited movement in attendance percentages at this stage."},"t3":{"measure":"Reduction in number of pupils <75%; pupil voice indicates stronger sense of belonging in Art & Drama; case studies of pupils whose attendance has improved.","progress":"Momentum building. Several previously persistent low-attenders show sustained improvement, particularly ASC pupils engaged through nurture and creative tasks. Pastoral Care report stronger faculty engagement in the attendance workflow."},"t4":{"measure":"End-of-year attendance data compared with August baseline; case studies finalised; success celebrated through faculty displays and exhibitions.","progress":"Clear positive trend by year-end: targeted cohort attendance improved, with strongest gains for ASC and care-experienced pupils. Restorative early-contact approach now embedded as standard practice and will continue in 2026–27 with a stronger Term 1 launch."}}},{"id":"gc1m1-2","commitment":"Creative engagement and nurture projects for ASC and care-experienced pupils.","subject":"Both","lead":"S. MacLean / M. Gallacher / K. Nutt / S. Airdrie","successMeasure":"Pupils report stronger sense of belonging and engagement.","dataArea":"Faculty referral data and Pastoral Care information showed ASC and care-experienced pupils were overrepresented in the <75% attendance cohort and reported lower confidence in mainstream classroom settings. Pupil voice gathered through Support for Learning highlighted a need for smaller, regulated creative spaces.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Social & Emotional Learning (+4 months); Glasgow City Council 'Nurturing City' principles; Education Scotland guidance on Nurturing Approaches. Evidence shows that nurture-based and creative interventions build belonging, regulation and engagement for pupils with ACEs and ASC.","resources":"In-service Day time to develop nurture-informed practice; Pedagogy Pod focused on inclusion and ASC-friendly pedagogy; Faculty meeting time to plan and review small-group projects; Hive / Support for Learning partnership; Art as Nurture programme led by M. Gallacher; nurture sessions led by S. Airdrie.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 3.1 – How effectively are our creative engagement and nurture projects supporting belonging, regulation and attendance for ASC and care-experienced pupils? What does pupil voice tell us about safe spaces within the faculty?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Lunchtime Drama club and Art club timetabled; target list of ASC / care-experienced pupils agreed with Support for Learning; first cohort referred via the Hive.","progress":"Clubs launched with steady early attendance. Art as Nurture (M. Gallacher) established a calm, structured environment; S. Airdrie's nurture sessions began running alongside SfL referrals. Some pupils engaged immediately; others required individual reassurance and follow-up."},"t2":{"measure":"Attendance and engagement registers for lunchtime clubs; first cycle of pupil voice gathered; observable regulation and participation noted in Art as Nurture sessions.","progress":"Sustained engagement from a core group of ASC pupils in Art as Nurture and in S. Airdrie's nurture sessions. Variable picture for care-experienced pupils — some highly engaged, others reluctant to attend in larger settings. Pastoral Care reported positive feedback from a number of parents."},"t3":{"measure":"Case studies of named pupils; pupil voice indicating sense of belonging; attendance trend data for cohort compared to Term 1 baseline.","progress":"Clear individual success stories emerging — several pupils whose mainstream attendance improved cite the nurture creative spaces as a reason. Equally honest reflection: a small group remained disengaged despite repeated outreach and will need a different approach in 2026–27."},"t4":{"measure":"End-of-year pupil voice and case study evidence collated; nurture work celebrated through faculty exhibition / performance pieces; planning underway for 2026–27 cohort.","progress":"Mixed but meaningful impact: nurture and creative engagement clearly worked for the majority of engaged pupils, with attendance and belonging measurably improved. Lessons learned around hard-to-reach pupils will inform a refined model for 2026–27, including earlier identification and stronger DYW / external partner links."}}},{"id":"gc1m1-3","commitment":"Celebrate success through updated faculty displays, performances, and exhibitions.","subject":"Both","lead":"S. MacLean / M. Gallacher / K. Nutt / S. Airdrie","successMeasure":"Parental feedback and attendance data show positive trends.","dataArea":"Pupil voice and a faculty environment audit indicated that displays were tired and pupil work was insufficiently celebrated outside the classroom. Combined with attendance data showing lower engagement in target groups, this identified profile-raising and visible celebration as a key driver of belonging.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Behaviour Interventions and SEL (+4 months) recognise visible recognition of pupil work as a contributor to engagement and self-efficacy. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 3.1 (Ensuring wellbeing, equality and inclusion) and QI 3.2 (Raising attainment and achievement) – pupil ownership of achievement supports both belonging and progression.","resources":"In-service Day time to plan showcase calendar; Pedagogy Pod time to share approaches to celebrating learning; Faculty meeting time for events planning; partnerships with Beacons Arts Centre and National Theatre Connections; performance budget for sets and costumes; faculty corridor display refresh (carried forward into 2026–27).","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 3.1 / 3.2 – How effectively are we using public celebration of pupil work to build belonging, raise aspirations and support attendance? Are our displays, performances and exhibitions reaching the pupils who most need to feel valued?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Showcase calendar agreed for the year; National Theatre Connections rehearsals underway; display audit completed identifying corridors needing refresh.","progress":"Strong launch through National Theatre Connections rehearsals. Pupil engagement with rehearsals high, including some pupils from the target attendance cohort. Display refresh identified as a priority but limited progress against this strand in Term 1."},"t2":{"measure":"S3 Drama performance evening delivered; National Theatre Connections performed in school and at Beacons Arts Centre; pupil voice gathered post-event.","progress":"Significant success: pupils performed at the Beacons Arts Centre and in school as part of National Theatre Connections, providing a high-profile platform. Pupil voice reported pride and a stronger sense of belonging. Faculty corridor displays remained largely unchanged."},"t3":{"measure":"Photography showcase / exhibition delivered; planning for end-of-year Romeo and Juliet performance underway; ongoing pupil voice on profile of pupil work.","progress":"Photography showcase generated strong pupil and parental engagement, raising the subject's profile. Senior Drama rehearsals for Romeo and Juliet building momentum. Corridor display refresh remains an outstanding action — work-in-progress that has not yet caught up with the strength of the live showcase strand."},"t4":{"measure":"End-of-year Art & Design exhibition; Romeo and Juliet performance; year-end pupil voice and parental feedback on celebration of pupil work.","progress":"Live showcase strand delivered very well — multiple high-profile performances (S3, National Connections at Beacons, Romeo and Juliet) and Art & Design / Photography exhibitions raised the faculty's profile and pupil pride. Honest reflection: corridor display refresh was not progressed this year and is a clear next-step priority for 2026–27. Performance and exhibition engagement is supporting the belonging strand of the attendance work."}}}]},"gc1m2":{"challenge":"Challenge 1: To provide an inclusive education meeting the needs of all learners","mission":"Mission 2: Embed Positive Behaviour, Equality, and UNCRC","commitments":[{"id":"gc1m2-1","commitment":"Consistent restorative approaches and ABC training implemented in all lessons.","subject":"Both","lead":"S. Airdrie / M. Gallacher","successMeasure":"Reduction in referrals and Duty SLT calls.","dataArea":"SEEMiS and Duty SLT call data showed referrals from the faculty had been creeping up over recent sessions, signalling a need to reset behaviour expectations and embed consistent restorative practice. Staff voice in faculty meetings supported the case for a shared, evidence-based approach.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Behaviour Interventions (+4 months). Restorative and ABC (Antecedent–Behaviour–Consequence) approaches are supported by the evidence base as effective in reducing low-level disruption and improving classroom climate. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 3.1 (Ensuring wellbeing, equality and inclusion) and the school's Promoting Positive Behaviour and Equality Policy.","resources":"In-service Day time delivered ABC and restorative training for the full faculty; Pedagogy Pod on relational classroom practice; Faculty meeting time to revisit and quality-assure approaches; behaviour policy reference materials and shared restorative scripts.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 3.1 – How consistently are restorative approaches being applied across all classrooms in the faculty? To what extent has ABC training reduced low-level disruption, referrals and Duty SLT calls?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"ABC training delivered to all faculty staff; shared restorative scripts agreed; baseline referral data captured.","progress":"Full faculty completed ABC training in Term 1, providing a shared framework. Common restorative scripts agreed across the team. Some natural variation in confidence in early application, with experienced practitioners modelling for newer colleagues."},"t2":{"measure":"Referral data tracked against baseline; staff peer observation focused on restorative language; pupil voice on classroom climate.","progress":"Referrals showing early downward trend compared with Term 1 baseline. Restorative language increasingly visible in classrooms; pupils reporting that disagreements are 'talked through' rather than escalated. Some inconsistency in approach between staff still evident."},"t3":{"measure":"Continued referral data review; faculty self-evaluation against restorative practice; pupil voice on fairness and consistency.","progress":"Restorative practice now the default in the majority of classrooms. Mostly consistent application across the team, with a small number of areas for further development identified through self-evaluation. Pupil voice highlights a calmer, fairer classroom climate."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of referrals and Duty SLT calls compared with start-of-year baseline; staff and pupil voice; case studies of pupils where restorative approach changed the trajectory.","progress":"Measurable reduction in referrals and Duty SLT calls from the faculty across the year. ABC and restorative practice now embedded as the faculty norm, with mostly consistent application — honest reflection that one or two staff would benefit from further coaching, which will form a 2026–27 priority. Strong contribution to the wider GC1 inclusion mission."}}},{"id":"gc1m2-2","commitment":"Review and develop thinking / reflection space and how this is used in the faculty to promote positive behaviour.","subject":"Both","lead":"S. Airdrie / M. Gallacher","successMeasure":"Pupils use reflection space to reset; reduction in escalations.","dataArea":"Staff and pupil voice highlighted a gap between the restorative ethos staff wanted to model and the physical environment available to support it — there was no consistent, calm space within the faculty for regulation, restorative conversations or pupil reflection on learning. Cross-linked with the GC2 M2 redesign of creative spaces.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Behaviour Interventions (+4 months) and SEL (+4 months); Education Scotland 'Nurturing Approaches' guidance; UNCRC Article 12 (right to be heard) and Article 31 (right to rest and play). Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 3.1 (wellbeing) and QI 1.2 (leadership of learning – environment as the third teacher).","resources":"Pedagogy Pod on relational practice and environment design; Faculty meeting time to scope and review the space; in-service time to plan a staged rollout; furniture and resources for the space (funding TBC); cross-linked with the GC2 M2 'repurpose creative spaces' workstream led by R. McColm / T. Livingstone.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 3.1 / 1.2 – How well does our physical environment support positive behaviour, regulation and pupil voice? To what extent is the reflection space used consistently across staff to promote restorative practice and pupil thinking?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Space identified within the faculty; staff consultation on intended uses (regulation, restorative conversations, reflection / journaling); initial expectations agreed.","progress":"Scoping conversations held with staff and pupils. Clear consensus on the three intended functions of the space — regulation, restorative dialogue, and pupil reflection on learning — but the space remained in development rather than operational by end of Term 1."},"t2":{"measure":"Space partially in use for regulation and restorative conversations; staff voice on usage patterns; pupil voice on accessibility.","progress":"Space began to be used in a limited way for time-out / regulation and restorative conversations. Uptake variable: some staff embedded use of the space into their routine response; others did not yet draw on it. Reflection / journaling use not yet established."},"t3":{"measure":"Tracker of space usage; faculty self-evaluation against intended uses; pupil voice on whether the space feels safe and useful.","progress":"Use of the space for regulation and restorative dialogue more consistent than Term 2 but still developing. Pupil reflection / journaling use beginning to emerge in a small number of classes. Profile-raising activity with staff identified as a next step."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of how the space has been used; staff and pupil voice; planning for full operationalisation and physical refresh in 2026–27, aligned to the GC2 M2 spaces redesign.","progress":"Honest year-end position: foundations laid and the concept of a faculty reflection space is now established in faculty thinking. Use is developing but inconsistent across staff, and the physical fit-out is incomplete. Carried into 2026–27 as a priority alongside the wider creative spaces redesign, with a clear remit to embed routine use across the team."}}},{"id":"gc1m2-3","commitment":"Curriculum reflects diversity through inclusive artists, playwrights, and designers.","subject":"Both","lead":"S. Airdrie / M. Gallacher","successMeasure":"Pupil work demonstrates inclusive values.","dataArea":"Pupil voice and a faculty curriculum audit identified that the range of artists and playwrights routinely studied did not yet fully reflect the diversity of pupils in the school. Female and non-binary practitioners in particular were under-represented in unit planning, especially in the BGE.","research":"Education Scotland 'Promoting and Developing Race Equality and Anti-Racist Education' guidance; UNCRC Articles 12, 29 and 30; GTCS Professional Standards (Social Justice / Sustaining Career-Long Professional Learning). Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 2.2 (Curriculum) and QI 3.1 (Ensuring wellbeing, equality and inclusion).","resources":"In-service Day time to begin a faculty diversity audit of texts, artists and designers; Pedagogy Pod on inclusive curriculum design; Faculty meeting time to revise unit planners; collaboration with the school's RRS / Equalities lead.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 2.2 / 3.1 – To what extent does our curriculum reflect the diversity of our pupils and wider society? How visible are female, non-binary and global majority artists and playwrights in unit planning and in pupil work?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Diversity audit of current curriculum content commenced; agreement to deliberately programme female and non-binary playwrights and artists into BGE and senior phase units.","progress":"Audit started, with staff identifying gaps in representation across BGE and senior phase units. Initial swaps of practitioners into unit planning agreed. Early-stage work — change visible at planning level but not yet in classrooms."},"t2":{"measure":"Revised unit plans in use; classroom resources updated; initial pupil voice on representation in their learning.","progress":"Female and non-binary playwrights and artists now explicitly programmed into a number of BGE units. Pupils responding positively to broader reference points; senior phase pupils beginning to reference these practitioners independently."},"t3":{"measure":"Folio and evaluation evidence; pupil voice; faculty self-evaluation against the diversity audit.","progress":"Some senior phase folios beginning to reference a broader range of practitioners, suggesting the curriculum changes are starting to shape pupil thinking. BGE pupil voice positive. Honest reflection: representation of global majority and disabled / neurodiverse practitioners is less developed than the gender strand."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of diversity audit; sample of pupil work analysed for breadth of references; planning for a wider audit (race, disability, LGBTQ+) in 2026–27.","progress":"Strand started this year and has shifted faculty thinking and unit planning. Visible in pupil work in pockets — strongest in senior folios. Foundations laid for a fuller audit and rollout in 2026–27, with race, disability and LGBTQ+ representation identified as the next priorities."}}},{"id":"gc1m2-4","commitment":"UNCRC articles referenced in unit planning and visible across classrooms.","subject":"Both","lead":"S. Airdrie / M. Gallacher","successMeasure":"Rights-based practice embedded in learning intentions and discussions.","dataArea":"Whole-school direction of travel toward rights-based practice combined with a faculty environment audit: class charters were present in most rooms, but UNCRC Articles were not yet referenced in unit planning or in learning intentions. Pupil voice indicated awareness of 'rights' as a concept without being able to name specific Articles.","research":"UNCRC (incorporated into Scots law in 2024), with Articles 12 (right to be heard), 29 (aims of education), 30 (culture and identity) and 31 (rest, play and cultural life) of particular relevance to Art & Drama; UNICEF UK Rights Respecting Schools framework; Education Scotland guidance on Children's Rights. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 3.1 (Ensuring wellbeing, equality and inclusion).","resources":"In-service Day time on UNCRC in subject planning; Pedagogy Pod linking restorative practice, reflection space and rights-based language as one integrated culture; Faculty meeting time to embed Articles into unit planners; class charter materials and displays.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 3.1 – How visibly are children's rights embedded in our planning, classrooms and pupil dialogue? Are pupils able to articulate which UNCRC Articles their learning supports, and how does this connect to restorative practice in the faculty?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Class charters displayed in the majority of classrooms; faculty agreement that UNCRC will be embedded into unit planners; baseline pupil voice on awareness of rights.","progress":"Charters visible in most rooms gave pupils an immediate point of reference. Honest position: UNCRC Articles were not yet referenced in unit planning at the start of session — the work this year has been about establishing the cultural foundations through restorative practice and the reflection space."},"t2":{"measure":"Pupil voice on rights awareness; initial draft unit-planner template including UNCRC references.","progress":"Charters routinely used as reference points in restorative conversations, integrating the GC1 M2 strands into one rights-based culture in classrooms. Unit planner work began but Articles are not yet consistently referenced in written planning."},"t3":{"measure":"Sample of unit plans reviewed for UNCRC references; pupil voice on which rights they can name and link to their learning.","progress":"Visible classroom culture continues to develop — pupils more frequently use rights-based language in restorative conversations. Unit planning lags behind classroom practice: Articles are emerging in some planners but inconsistent. Identified as the priority action for 2026–27."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of unit planning and classroom evidence; planning for systematic embedding of UNCRC Articles into unit planners and learning intentions in 2026–27.","progress":"Mixed year-end picture. Strong cultural foundation through class charters, restorative practice and integration with the reflection space — pupils experience a rights-respecting classroom climate. Honest reflection: UNCRC Articles are not yet referenced in unit planning, which is the single largest piece of work to take into 2026–27. Will be linked explicitly to the diversity-of-curriculum strand (Row 3) so both develop together."}}}]},"gc2m1":{"challenge":"Challenge 2: All young people experience high-quality learning, teaching & assessment","mission":"Mission 1: Fully embed the Learning & Teaching Policy","commitments":[{"id":"gc2m1-1","commitment":"Strengthen literacy across both subjects — essay scaffolds, design vocabulary, contextual analysis.","subject":"Both","lead":"All Staff","successMeasure":"Improved literacy in written and design components.","dataArea":"Whole-school literacy audit and the School Improvement Plan identified literacy as a cross-curricular priority. Faculty SQA analysis confirmed that written components (Higher Drama written paper and N5 / Higher Art & Design written elements) were the main limiting factor on pupil outcomes.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Literacy across the Curriculum (+6 months); Education Scotland 'Improving Literacy: A Framework for Action'. Evidence shows that explicit teaching of subject-specific vocabulary, sentence structures and writing scaffolds raises attainment in written components, particularly when integrated into routine practice rather than treated as an add-on. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 2.3 (Learning, teaching and assessment).","resources":"In-service Day time on disciplinary literacy in Art and Drama; Pedagogy Pod on writing scaffolds and modelling; Faculty meeting time to share approaches; whole-school literacy strategy materials.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 2.3 / 3.2 – How explicitly are we teaching the literacy skills pupils need to succeed in written components of Art and Drama? What evidence in pupil work shows our scaffolds, vocabulary teaching and modelling are working?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Faculty commitment to literacy strand; whole-school literacy priorities shared with staff; initial discussions on subject-specific scaffolds.","progress":"Literacy positioned as a faculty priority and reference to whole-school literacy strategy made in faculty meetings. Honest reflection: no specific faculty-level scaffolds, glossaries or pupil exemplars were rolled out in Term 1 — focus diverted by other priorities."},"t2":{"measure":"Sample pupil written work; staff voice on confidence delivering literacy scaffolds; faculty meeting agenda items on literacy.","progress":"Some classroom-level practice in modelling written responses, particularly at Higher level, but no faculty-wide system of scaffolds, glossaries or exemplars in place. Pupil written work shows the same patterns as previous sessions."},"t3":{"measure":"Pupil work analysis; SQA-style timed essays for Higher Drama; folio written elements moderation.","progress":"Continued individual good practice from staff in modelling written work but limited faculty-wide consistency. The strand has not received the focused attention originally intended; impact on pupil written outcomes not yet measurable."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of written components in folios and exam preparation; honest evaluation of progress; planning for a stronger literacy push in 2026–27 aligned to the GC3 M2 Higher Drama written exam priority.","progress":"Year-end honest reflection: this strand did not receive enough focused attention in 2025–26. Literacy remains the single largest barrier to written component attainment, particularly in Higher Drama. Carried forward as a clear 2026–27 priority with a planned faculty-level rollout of scaffolds, design vocabulary glossaries and exemplars, anchored to the school literacy strategy and tied directly to the GC3 M2 Higher Drama written exam improvement work."}}},{"id":"gc2m1-2","commitment":"Pedagogy pods and practitioner enquiry focused on effective teaching practices. All staff engage and share knowledge of own pedagogical research.","subject":"Both","lead":"All Staff","successMeasure":"Shared pedagogical practice evident across faculty; staff articulate enquiry findings.","dataArea":"Staff voice in faculty meetings and through Professional Review and Development (PRD) conversations identified an appetite for more collaborative pedagogical discussion. Whole-school direction of travel toward a research-informed, enquiry-based professional culture provided the wider driver, with Pedagogy Pods running across the school this session.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Collaborative Learning / Professional Development; Education Scotland 'Teaching Scotland's Future' (Donaldson) principles; GTCS Standards for Career-Long Professional Learning. Practitioner enquiry and pedagogical collaboration are evidenced as among the most effective levers for raising consistency and quality of classroom practice. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 1.2 (Leadership of learning) and QI 2.3 (Learning, teaching and assessment).","resources":"Whole-school Pedagogy Pod time scheduled into the calendar; In-service Day time linked to pod themes; Faculty meeting time for staff to share findings back into the team; GTCS Professional Update reflection as the wider PRD frame.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 1.2 / 2.3 – How effectively are staff engaging with pedagogical research and enquiry, and how is that shaping practice in our classrooms? What evidence shows that pod and enquiry work is changing what pupils experience?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Pedagogy Pods scheduled and faculty staff allocated to cross-school groups; initial themes shared across the team.","progress":"Pods launched on schedule with all faculty staff participating in cross-school groups covering a range of pedagogical themes. Early sessions focused on individual pod priorities; sharing back into the faculty was informal at this stage."},"t2":{"measure":"Staff voice on impact of pod work; faculty meeting agenda items where staff share pod learning; classroom observations / learning visits.","progress":"All faculty staff continued to engage actively in their cross-school pods. Faculty meeting time used for short staff shares — informal but valued, with strategies from differentiation, AfL and digital pods feeding back into faculty practice."},"t3":{"measure":"Continued staff shares; informal practitioner enquiry reflections; evidence of changed practice in classrooms.","progress":"Collaborative culture noticeably stronger than at the start of the year — staff regularly reference 'something I picked up in pod' in discussions. Practitioner enquiry happening informally rather than as documented enquiry cycles. Developing rather than fully embedded."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of pod and enquiry work; staff voice on impact; planning for more formal enquiry documentation in 2026–27.","progress":"Solid year of engagement: all staff participated in Pedagogy Pods and there is clear evidence the culture is moving in the right direction, with shared language and shared strategies more visible. Honest reflection: practitioner enquiry remains informal rather than formally documented, which limits the evidence base. Carried into 2026–27 with a plan to formalise individual enquiry cycles linked to GTCS Professional Update and to the GC2 M2 curriculum challenge work."}}},{"id":"gc2m1-3","commitment":"Use digital tools (OneNote, Teams) for evidence gathering and differentiation; SatchelOne to support home learning.","subject":"Both","lead":"All Staff","successMeasure":"Majority of folios and written tasks completed on time; OneNote evidence consistent.","dataArea":"Whole-school digital strategy identified OneNote (evidence) and SatchelOne (home learning and parental communication) as the consistent platforms for all faculties. Faculty audit showed variable usage across staff and year groups, with senior phase folio work running ahead of BGE practice and home learning communication still developing.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Using Digital Technology to Improve Learning (+5 months); Education Scotland 'Digital Learning and Teaching Strategy for Scotland'. Evidence shows digital tools are most effective when used to support specific pedagogical purposes (evidence-gathering, accessibility, differentiation, home communication) rather than as ends in themselves. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 2.3 (Learning, teaching and assessment) and QI 2.5 (Family learning).","resources":"In-service Day time on OneNote and SatchelOne workflows; Pedagogy Pod on digital differentiation; Faculty meeting time to share approaches; Microsoft 365 accessibility tools (Immersive Reader, dictation); whole-school digital lead support; pupil and parent guides for SatchelOne.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 2.3 / 2.5 – How consistently are we using OneNote to gather pupil evidence and SatchelOne to communicate home? How are digital tools supporting differentiation (Immersive Reader, differentiated pages, pupil-led photo evidence) for our most vulnerable learners?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Faculty agreement that OneNote is the default for evidence and SatchelOne the default for homework; staff baseline audit of current practice; shared OneNote structures agreed for senior phase courses.","progress":"Senior phase OneNote structures embedded quickly, with pupils uploading photos of practical work and folio evidence. SatchelOne homework setting routine in S1 and beginning to extend. Some staff lagging in adoption; identified as a focus for follow-up CLPL."},"t2":{"measure":"Sample OneNote notebooks reviewed; SatchelOne homework completion data; parental engagement data via SatchelOne; staff voice on confidence with digital tools.","progress":"Pupil-led photo evidence in OneNote becoming routine in senior phase Art and Drama. Differentiated OneNote pages and Immersive Reader use emerging as concrete differentiation strategies. SatchelOne strong in S1 but inconsistent further up the school."},"t3":{"measure":"Digital differentiation strategies tracked; pupil voice on accessibility; SatchelOne homework return rates and parent engagement.","progress":"Three differentiation strategies clearly visible — pupil-led OneNote photo evidence, differentiated OneNote pages by group, and Immersive Reader / text-to-speech for written tasks — particularly supporting EAL pupils. SatchelOne still developing into S2 and above; consistency across all staff remains the main barrier."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of OneNote and SatchelOne usage; staff voice on remaining barriers; planning for full faculty consistency in 2026–27.","progress":"Year-end position: developing rather than embedded. OneNote shows real strength in senior phase practical evidence and emerging power as a differentiation tool (especially Immersive Reader for EAL). SatchelOne strong in S1 with a clear plan to extend through S2 and beyond. Honest reflection: digital consistency across all staff remains the headline challenge — focused 2026–27 CLPL planned for staff who have been slower to adopt, alongside extension of SatchelOne to all year groups."}}},{"id":"gc2m1-4","commitment":"Consistent feedback and assessment through departmental moderation.","subject":"Both","lead":"All Staff","successMeasure":"Consistent feedback and self-reflection evident in pupil work.","dataArea":"SQA results analysis and internal review identified some variation in assessment judgements across staff and inconsistency in the depth and style of feedback given to pupils. School improvement plan also highlighted consistent feedback and assessment as a priority across all faculties.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Feedback (+6 months); SQA Understanding Standards guidance; Education Scotland 'Moderation Cycle'. Evidence shows that consistent, criteria-referenced feedback combined with regular cross-marking and exemplar discussion is one of the most powerful levers on pupil attainment, particularly at SQA level. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 2.3 (Learning, teaching and assessment) and QI 3.2 (Raising attainment and achievement).","resources":"Termly moderation slots built into the faculty calendar; In-service Day time for cross-marking sessions; Pedagogy Pod on feedback that moves learning forward; Faculty meeting time on shared exemplars; cross-school SQA Understanding Standards events; SQA verifier visit feedback.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 2.3 / 3.2 – How consistently are pupils across the faculty receiving high-quality, criteria-referenced feedback? How robust is our moderation in ensuring fairness and accuracy of assessment judgements, and how is this evidence used to improve teaching?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Moderation calendar agreed for the year with termly internal cross-marking slots; SQA Understanding Standards dates booked; shared exemplar bank discussed.","progress":"Moderation calendar in place and first internal cross-marking session held. Staff engaged constructively; minor differences in interpretation of criteria identified and discussed. Cross-school Understanding Standards dates confirmed."},"t2":{"measure":"Internal cross-marking session 2 completed; Understanding Standards events attended; pupil work sampling showing impact of moderation discussions; staff voice on feedback practice.","progress":"Staff attended SQA Understanding Standards events and brought learning back into faculty meetings. Internal cross-marking continuing on schedule. Feedback to pupils mostly consistent in approach with some variation in style remaining across the team."},"t3":{"measure":"Continued moderation cycle; SQA verifier visit feedback; sample pupil work analysed for consistency of feedback and grade alignment.","progress":"Moderation infrastructure performing well — calendar honoured, cross-marking and Understanding Standards work happening as planned, verifier feedback informing practice. However, depth of impact on day-to-day classroom feedback to pupils is harder to evidence; this is where the limited progress sits."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of moderation cycle and feedback consistency; planning for 2026–27 to deepen the impact on day-to-day pupil feedback as well as final assessment judgements.","progress":"Strong moderation infrastructure ran throughout the year — termly internal cross-marking, SQA Understanding Standards events, verifier feedback and shared exemplar work all happened on plan. Year-end honest reflection: the visible impact on routine pupil feedback in classrooms has been more limited than hoped. The structure is now in place; the priority for 2026–27 is to translate that moderation work into sharper, more consistent classroom feedback that moves pupil learning forward."}}}]},"gc2m2":{"challenge":"Challenge 2: All young people experience high-quality learning, teaching & assessment","mission":"Mission 2: Develop curriculum to provide challenge","commitments":[{"id":"gc2m2-1","commitment":"Embed meta-skills in all units and pupil reflection work.","subject":"Both","lead":"S. MacLean / M. Gallacher / R. McColm / T. Livingstone","successMeasure":"Pupils articulate their meta-skills confidently.","dataArea":"Whole-school direction of travel toward an explicit meta-skills curriculum, supported by DYW analysis showing pupils struggle to articulate transferable skills in interviews and college applications. Faculty audit confirmed meta-skills were being developed implicitly through practical Art and Drama work but were not labelled, evidenced or reflected on with pupils.","research":"Skills Development Scotland (SDS) Meta-Skills model — Self-Management, Social Intelligence, Innovation. EEF Toolkit – Metacognition and Self-Regulation (+7 months); DYW Skills 4.0 framework; Education Scotland 'Career Education Standard 3–18'. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 2.2 (Curriculum), QI 2.3 (Learning, teaching and assessment) and QI 3.2 (Raising attainment and achievement).","resources":"In-service Day time to introduce the SDS Meta-Skills model to faculty staff; Pedagogy Pod on metacognition and pupil reflection; Faculty meeting time to revise unit planners and reflection prompts; SDS meta-skills resources and pupil-facing language guides; DYW links for real-world skill exemplars.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 2.2 / 3.2 – How explicitly are meta-skills (Self-Management, Social Intelligence, Innovation) named, developed and reflected on in our units? To what extent can pupils articulate the meta-skills they are developing through Art and Drama, and link them to future pathways?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"SDS Meta-Skills model introduced to faculty staff; agreement to embed reflection prompts in BGE and senior phase units; pilot units identified.","progress":"Faculty staff introduced to the SDS Meta-Skills framework with strong initial buy-in. Pilot reflection prompts agreed for a small number of units. Honest reflection: no immediate visible change in pupil work in Term 1 — frame established, embedding still to do."},"t2":{"measure":"Sample of pupil reflection work; staff voice on confidence using meta-skills language; pilot unit feedback.","progress":"Pockets of strong practice emerging in pilot units (notably in S3 Drama and senior Art folios), where pupils are beginning to encounter meta-skills language. Across the faculty, embedding is uneven — units not in the pilot have not yet adopted the language consistently."},"t3":{"measure":"Pupil voice on meta-skills awareness; analysis of pupil reflection / folio evaluations for meta-skills references; faculty self-evaluation.","progress":"Pockets of strength continue in pilot units; whole-faculty consistency remains the gap. Pupil voice shows that the vocabulary of Self-Management, Social Intelligence and Innovation is not yet routine for most pupils. Reflection on meta-skills is not yet visible in the majority of pupil work."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of meta-skills embedding; staff and pupil voice; planning for a full faculty rollout in 2026–27 aligned with the curriculum progression map work.","progress":"Honest year-end position: framework established and pockets of strong practice exist, but embedding is not yet faculty-wide and pupils' meta-skills vocabulary is still developing. Identified as a 2026–27 priority, with a clear plan to extend pilot practice across all units, link reflection to folio cover sheets and BGE PBL evaluations, and develop pupil-facing language guides. Will be progressed alongside the S1–S6 progression map (next row)."}}},{"id":"gc2m2-2","commitment":"Develop and refine S1–S2 Project-Based Learning linked to Es & Os.","subject":"Both","lead":"S. MacLean / M. Gallacher / R. McColm / T. Livingstone","successMeasure":"Clear S1–S6 curriculum progression map with visible skills development.","dataArea":"Faculty curriculum review identified that the BGE offer in Art and Drama relied on a series of shorter units which limited the depth of project work and the visible link to Experiences & Outcomes. Pupil voice and SQA uptake data also showed a need for stronger, more engaging BGE experiences to drive sustained interest into senior phase.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Metacognition and Self-Regulation (+7 months) and Collaborative Learning (+5 months); Education Scotland 'Curriculum for Excellence: Building from the Statement Appendix'; Expressive Arts Es & Os benchmarks. Evidence supports extended project-based learning as a vehicle for deeper skills development, pupil ownership and authentic application of Es & Os. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 2.2 (Curriculum) and QI 2.3 (Learning, teaching and assessment).","resources":"In-service Day time to design the S2 final-term project; Pedagogy Pod on PBL design principles; Faculty meeting time to map Es & Os into project units; CfE Es & Os benchmarks; pupil-facing project briefs; cross-link to the GC1 M2 diverse curriculum row for inclusive practitioner references.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 2.2 / 2.3 – How well does our S1–S2 PBL provision build depth, challenge and meta-skills? How clearly are Expressive Arts, Literacy and Health & Wellbeing Es & Os woven through our projects, and is there a coherent progression into senior phase?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Scope of S1 and S2 PBL units agreed; Es & Os mapping started; project briefs drafted.","progress":"Faculty agreed to design a full S2 final-term project as the flagship piece of PBL work for 2025–26, with an S1 equivalent to follow. Es & Os mapping for Expressive Arts, Literacy and Health & Wellbeing built into the initial planning."},"t2":{"measure":"S2 project brief finalised; Es & Os mapping documented; teaching resources prepared.","progress":"S2 project brief and resources fully developed by end of Term 2, ready to launch in the final term. Strong staff engagement in the design process. Initial scoping for the parallel S1 project also underway."},"t3":{"measure":"S2 project launched and running; pupil work and engagement evidenced; planning for S1 project for June continued.","progress":"S2 project launched successfully with high pupil engagement. Pupils visibly more independent and project-managing their own work, with clear skills gains in collaboration, communication and creative problem-solving. S1 project for June development on track."},"t4":{"measure":"S2 project completed and evaluated; S1 project delivered in June; pupil work and voice gathered; planning for S1–S6 progression map work in 2026–27.","progress":"Strong year for this strand. The S2 final-term project was a notable success — high pupil engagement, clear skills gains and a tangible final outcome. S1 project for June completes the BGE PBL offer. Honest reflection: the explicit S1–S6 progression map is not yet on paper and is the priority for 2026–27, ensuring this strong BGE work feeds visibly into senior phase choices and skills development."}}},{"id":"gc2m2-3","commitment":"Improve tracking and attainment discussions within faculty meetings.","subject":"Both","lead":"S. MacLean / M. Gallacher / R. McColm / T. Livingstone","successMeasure":"Tracking data informs targeted support; non-progressing pupils identified early.","dataArea":"SQA results analysis and review of internal tracking practice identified that attainment discussions were strongest at SEEMiS reporting points but less consistent in between, with non-progressing pupils often identified later than ideal. A faculty-level supplementary tracker was needed to enable more frequent, evidence-led conversations.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Feedback (+6 months); Education Scotland 'Looking Inwards, Outwards and Forwards' self-evaluation framework. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 1.1 (Self-evaluation for self-improvement), QI 2.3 (Learning, teaching and assessment) and QI 3.2 (Raising attainment and achievement). Evidence shows that regular, data-informed professional dialogue between teachers is among the strongest drivers of consistent assessment judgements and timely intervention.","resources":"Whole-school SEEMiS reporting as the primary tracking platform; faculty supplementary tracker (in development); termly dedicated faculty meeting time for attainment discussion; Pedagogy Pod on data-informed practice; in-service time for tracker design.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 1.1 / 3.2 – How effectively are we using tracking data to inform professional dialogue and pupil interventions? Are non-progressing pupils being identified early enough, and how do we evidence the impact of the support we put in place?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Termly attainment meeting calendar agreed; SEEMiS tracking processes confirmed; design of a faculty supplementary tracker initiated.","progress":"First termly attainment meeting held, focused on senior phase progress against working grades. Strong, professional discussion across the team. SEEMiS reporting cycle as the primary data source. Faculty supplementary tracker design started but not yet operational."},"t2":{"measure":"Sample meeting agendas / minutes; pupil progress data reviewed; interventions identified for named pupils.","progress":"Second termly attainment meeting completed with stronger senior phase data and clearer identification of pupils requiring support. BGE attainment discussion lighter than senior phase. Interventions for named pupils agreed but documented informally rather than tracked."},"t3":{"measure":"Continued termly meeting; SQA prelim data analysis; intervention logs reviewed; pupil voice for non-progressing pupils.","progress":"Senior phase attainment discussions clearly stronger than at the start of the year — data-informed, focused on individuals and on patterns. BGE discussions remain less developed, partly because the faculty supplementary tracker is not yet operational. Interventions still informal in many cases."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of tracking practice; planning for full rollout of the faculty supplementary tracker in 2026–27, plus a formalised intervention log.","progress":"Mixed year-end position. Termly dedicated meetings have become a real strength of faculty culture, and senior phase attainment conversations are noticeably sharper than 12 months ago. BGE discussions and the faculty supplementary tracker remain underdeveloped. Priorities for 2026–27: complete and embed the supplementary tracker, build BGE attainment into the termly cycle, and formalise the intervention log so impact can be evidenced."}}},{"id":"gc2m2-4","commitment":"Repurpose art and design spaces to include a photography studio and pupil wellbeing / reflection spaces to enhance engagement and wellbeing.","subject":"Art","lead":"R. McColm / T. Livingstone","successMeasure":"Redesigned creative spaces increase pupil engagement and ownership of learning.","dataArea":"Faculty environment audit and pupil voice identified that existing creative spaces were under-utilised and did not yet support the growing Photography offer or the wellbeing strand of the inclusion mission. Photography uptake had grown to a point where a dedicated studio environment was needed to sustain and extend high-quality teaching.","research":"EEF Toolkit – evidence on classroom environment as a contributing factor in engagement and wellbeing; Education Scotland 'Designing Spaces for Learning'; OECD 'Learning Environments Evaluation Programme' (LEEP). Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 1.2 (Leadership of learning – environment as the third teacher), QI 2.2 (Curriculum) and QI 3.1 (Ensuring wellbeing, equality and inclusion). Cross-linked with GC1 M2 reflection space row.","resources":"School capital budget for Photography studio fit-out (lighting, backdrops, digital workflow equipment); faculty staff time led by R. McColm and T. Livingstone for design and installation; In-service Day time for staff training on the new studio; Pedagogy Pod time on environment design; SQA Photography course resources.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 1.2 / 2.2 / 3.1 – How is our redesigned learning environment supporting pupil engagement, ownership and wellbeing? What evidence shows that the new Photography studio is improving the quality of pupil work and the breadth of the senior phase offer?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Photography studio design agreed; capital spend approved; first equipment ordered; pupil consultation on intended uses.","progress":"Studio fit-out commenced. Pupil consultation showed strong enthusiasm for the dedicated space. Initial use possible for some classes but full functionality not yet in place by end of Term 1."},"t2":{"measure":"Studio partially operational; pupil photography work evidenced in OneNote; first pupil exhibition / showcase use.","progress":"Photography studio now being used regularly by senior phase Photography classes, with lighting and backdrops available. Pupil ownership and pride in the space visibly improving — pupils referring to 'the studio' as their own working environment."},"t3":{"measure":"Continued use of studio for SQA folio work; pupil voice on impact on confidence and folio quality; planning for further refits across the remaining art / design spaces.","progress":"Photography studio embedded into routine teaching, with clear pupil ownership and visible improvements in pupil wellbeing and confidence in the space. Honest reflection: the wider art / design spaces and pupil reflection / wellbeing areas still require significant work — this strand is firmly carried forward to 2026–27."},"t4":{"measure":"End-of-year Photography showcase / exhibition using the new studio; pupil voice and folio evidence collated; design and costing for the next phase of spaces work.","progress":"Strong year for the Photography studio specifically — in development across the year, increasingly operational, and visibly improving pupil ownership and wellbeing in the senior phase. Honest year-end reflection: the wider redesign of art and design spaces, including pupil wellbeing / reflection areas, has not yet progressed and is the priority for 2026–27. Cross-linked with GC1 M2 reflection space, faculty corridor displays, and the GC2 M2 progression map work."}}}]},"gc3m1":{"challenge":"Challenge 3: Raising attainment and achievement for all learners","mission":"Mission 1: Increase attainment in Literacy & Numeracy (BGE) and refine approaches to tracking attainment","commitments":[{"id":"gc3m1-1","commitment":"Provide literacy scaffolds and design vocabulary for evaluations.","subject":"Both","lead":"Art Team / R. McColm / T. Livingstone","successMeasure":"Improved literacy and design performance at N5.","dataArea":"BGE pupil work review and N5 Art & Design results analysis identified that pupils' written evaluations consistently rely on descriptive language rather than Tier 3 design vocabulary, and that there is no shared faculty bank of scaffolds or exemplars. Pupil voice indicates uncertainty about 'what good written evaluation looks like' in Art and Design.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Literacy across the Curriculum (+6 months); Education Scotland 'Improving Literacy: A Framework for Action'; Quigley 'Closing the Vocabulary Gap'. Evidence consistently supports explicit teaching of subject-specific (Tier 3) vocabulary and written sentence-level scaffolds as among the most effective levers for raising attainment in design evaluations. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 2.3 (Learning, teaching and assessment) and QI 3.2 (Raising attainment and achievement).","resources":"In-service Day time for collaborative design of vocabulary banks and evaluation scaffolds; Pedagogy Pod on disciplinary literacy; Faculty meeting time to agree shared exemplars; school literacy lead support; OneNote space for shared faculty resources.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 2.3 / 3.2 – How explicitly are we teaching design vocabulary and written evaluation skills in BGE Art and Design? What evidence in pupil written work shows that scaffolds and vocabulary teaching are closing the gap on N5 written components?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Faculty agreement that BGE design vocabulary and written evaluation are a priority; initial audit of current scaffolds and pupil work; identification of N5 Design as the senior phase link point.","progress":"Faculty alignment confirmed and starting point established. Specific design vocabulary glossaries, sentence stems and exemplars were not produced in Term 1. Strand recognised as overlapping with the wider GC2 M1 literacy row, which similarly did not progress as planned."},"t2":{"measure":"Sample BGE pupil written evaluation work; staff voice on current practice; trial scaffolds in selected classes.","progress":"A small number of staff trialled written evaluation scaffolds in individual classes with positive informal results. No faculty-wide vocabulary bank or shared scaffold pack yet produced. Strong practice remains teacher-dependent rather than systematic."},"t3":{"measure":"Continued sampling of pupil written work; review of N5 Design folio written elements; mapping of progression from BGE to N5.","progress":"Picture remains variable: some BGE classes produce strong written evaluation work, others largely descriptive. The link from BGE vocabulary teaching to N5 Design written components is clear in theory but not yet operationalised through shared faculty resources."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end honest review of progress; design of a 2026–27 plan for shared design vocabulary, scaffolds and exemplars; alignment with the GC2 M1 literacy row and the GC3 M2 Higher / N5 written work priority.","progress":"Honest year-end reflection mirrors GC2 M1: this strand did not receive the focused attention originally planned. Faculty alignment on the priority is strong, but specific BGE design vocabulary banks, sentence stems and exemplars are still to be produced. Carried into 2026–27 as a clear deliverable, tied directly to the N5 Art & Design (Design) component priority and the GC2 M1 literacy work."}}},{"id":"gc3m1-2","commitment":"Integrate literacy / numeracy Es & Os into learning intentions and success criteria.","subject":"Both","lead":"Art Team / R. McColm / T. Livingstone","successMeasure":"Pupils apply numeracy in creative tasks confidently.","dataArea":"Whole-school Literacy and Numeracy across Learning audit identified inconsistent integration of Literacy and Numeracy Es & Os into subject-area Learning Intentions and Success Criteria. Faculty self-evaluation confirmed that while Art and Drama provide rich L&N opportunities (notably scale and proportion in design, and contextual evaluation writing), this is not yet explicit for pupils.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Literacy across the Curriculum (+6 months); Education Scotland 'Literacy and Numeracy across Learning' Es & Os and benchmarks; CfE 'Responsibility of All' principles. Evidence supports making cross-curricular L&N skills explicit through clear LIs and SC, with measurable improvement in pupils' ability to articulate and transfer skills. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 2.2 (Curriculum) and QI 3.2 (Raising attainment and achievement).","resources":"In-service Day time to revisit L&N Es & Os and benchmarks; Pedagogy Pod on LIs and SC quality; Faculty meeting time to share examples; school L&N coordinators; whole-school L&N strategy resources.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 2.2 / 3.2 – How consistently are Literacy and Numeracy Es & Os visible in our BGE Learning Intentions and Success Criteria, and are pupils able to articulate the L&N skills they are developing through Art and Drama?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Audit of current LIs and SC across BGE Art and Drama; agreement to integrate L&N Es & Os into unit planning; pilot LIs trialled in selected units.","progress":"Audit completed showing inconsistent integration of L&N Es & Os. Faculty agreement on intent. Initial planning-level changes started in a small number of units, particularly around measurement, scale and proportion in BGE Art / Design."},"t2":{"measure":"Sample LIs and SC reviewed; pupil voice on L&N skills awareness; staff voice on confidence with L&N integration.","progress":"Planning-level changes visible in some unit planners — measurement, scale and proportion now flagged as explicit numeracy outcomes in selected Art / Design units. Lesson-level LIs and SC still catching up; not yet routinely shared with pupils."},"t3":{"measure":"Continued sampling of LIs / SC; pupil reflections; review of progression from BGE numeracy to senior phase technical work.","progress":"Numeracy (measurement / scale / proportion) more visible than literacy at planning level. Pupils still struggle to name the L&N skills they are developing — implicit progress but limited explicit articulation. Strand is moving but unevenly."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of LIs and SC; analysis of pupil voice; planning for full faculty rollout in 2026–27 anchored to the school L&N strategy.","progress":"Developing year-end position. Planning-level integration of L&N Es & Os has begun, particularly for numeracy (measurement, scale, proportion) in BGE Art / Design. Honest reflection: implementation is inconsistent across staff and pupils do not yet routinely name the L&N skills they are developing. Carried into 2026–27 as a deliberate, faculty-wide rollout, tied to the Row 1 design vocabulary work and the L&N strategy school-wide."}}},{"id":"gc3m1-3","commitment":"Strengthen N5 Art & Design (Design element) through focused process teaching, exemplar analysis, and idea development.","subject":"Art","lead":"R. McColm / T. Livingstone","successMeasure":"Improved N5 Design component results; stronger idea development in folios.","dataArea":"SQA results analysis showed the N5 Art & Design (Design element) performing below national and local authority averages, and below the faculty's own Expressive folio outcomes. Internal review identified that pupils were strongest in research and final outcomes but weaker on idea development and design process documentation — the specific area being assessed.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Metacognition and Self-Regulation (+7 months) and Feedback (+6 months); SQA N5 Art & Design Course Specification and Understanding Standards exemplars; Education Scotland 'Looking Inwards, Outwards and Forwards' framework. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 2.3 (Learning, teaching and assessment) and QI 3.2 (Raising attainment and achievement).","resources":"In-service Day time for explicit design process teaching CLPL; staff attendance at SQA Understanding Standards events for N5 Art & Design; Pedagogy Pod on idea development pedagogy; exemplar bank of past pupil folios; verifier feedback materials; Faculty meeting time for moderation of design folios.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 2.3 / 3.2 – How explicitly are we teaching the design process — research, idea development, refinement, final outcome — to N5 Art & Design pupils? What evidence in pupil folios shows that exemplar analysis and SQA-informed teaching are closing the gap on the Design component?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"SQA Understanding Standards attendance booked; pupil cohort identified; exemplar folio bank assembled; explicit design process teaching sequence designed.","progress":"Strong start: staff attended SQA Understanding Standards events for N5 Art & Design and brought learning back into the classroom immediately. Exemplar folio analysis embedded as part of routine teaching. Pupils introduced to the explicit design process model."},"t2":{"measure":"Mid-year folio review against SQA benchmarks; pupil voice on understanding of design process; verifier feedback applied to planning.","progress":"Visible improvement in pupils' research and idea development pages of their Design folios — more sustained, more annotated, with stronger links between research and ideas. Final outcome quality emerging as the next area to focus on."},"t3":{"measure":"Folio progress review; explicit refinement and final outcome teaching; one-to-one tutorials with senior pupils; SQA Understanding Standards learning applied to feedback.","progress":"Continued strong process and idea development work in folios. Mid-folio outcomes showing visible improvement on previous cohorts. Final outcomes remain variable: high-attaining pupils producing strong final pieces, middle of the cohort still inconsistent in translating strong development work into refined final pieces."},"t4":{"measure":"Folios completed and submitted to SQA; pupil voice and folio evidence reviewed; year-end evaluation of the strand; planning for 2026–27 with focus on translating strong process work into stronger final outcomes.","progress":"Strongest strand of GC3 M1. SQA Understanding Standards attendance, exemplar analysis and explicit design process teaching have visibly improved pupils' research and idea development. Honest year-end reflection: final outcome quality is the residual gap — strong work in development isn't yet consistently translating into stronger final pieces. Awaiting SQA results to confirm impact on attainment. Carried forward to 2026–27 with focus on refinement and final outcome teaching, plus a 'Looking Outwards' visit to another school's Art department."}}},{"id":"gc3m1-4","commitment":"Adapt resources for EAL pupils and share strategies across staff.","subject":"Both","lead":"Art Team / R. McColm / T. Livingstone","successMeasure":"EAL pupils achieve improved access and outcomes.","dataArea":"School census data and faculty class lists confirm a small but growing EAL cohort, with pupils across a widening range of first languages. Faculty self-evaluation identified that individual staff were independently adapting practice but there was no shared resource bank or agreed strategy, leading to variable experiences for EAL pupils across classes.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Teaching Assistants / Targeted Interventions and Oral Language Interventions (+6 months); Education Scotland 'Learners who use English as an Additional Language' guidance; Bilingualism Matters research; SCILT (Scotland's National Centre for Languages) guidance on inclusive multilingual classrooms. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 2.4 (Personalised support) and QI 3.1 (Ensuring wellbeing, equality and inclusion).","resources":"Immersive Reader / Microsoft 365 accessibility tools (linked to GC2 M1 digital row); Microsoft Translator for slide translation; In-service Day time on EAL-inclusive pedagogy; Pedagogy Pod on differentiation; Faculty meeting time to share strategies; whole-school EAL coordinator / SfL liaison.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 2.4 / 3.1 – How effectively are we adapting resources, instructions and slides for our EAL learners, and to what extent are strategies being shared across faculty staff so all EAL pupils experience high-quality, accessible learning?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"EAL pupil list shared with faculty; baseline audit of current adaptations; agreement to use Immersive Reader as a default accessibility tool.","progress":"Faculty staff began routinely using Immersive Reader for written tasks; some staff started translating slides for EAL pupils. Initial good practice happening at individual teacher level. Honest reflection: no faculty-wide co-ordination at this stage."},"t2":{"measure":"Sample EAL pupil work; staff voice on adaptations being used; pupil voice from EAL learners.","progress":"Slide translation emerged as a notable area of progress this year, with several staff routinely producing translated versions of key resources for named EAL pupils. Immersive Reader use becoming routine. Simplified task instructions and dual-language resources used by some but not all staff."},"t3":{"measure":"Continued sampling of pupil work; pupil voice on accessibility; review of which strategies are working and for which pupils.","progress":"Mixed picture. Slide translation and Immersive Reader strategies clearly landing for several EAL pupils; simplified instructions and dual-language resources less consistently applied. Practice remains individual rather than shared — no consolidated resource bank yet exists."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of EAL strategies; pupil voice from EAL learners; planning for a shared faculty EAL resource bank and agreed default adaptations in 2026–27.","progress":"Emerging year-end position. Real progress on slide translation, Immersive Reader and individual staff adaptations — practice has improved, especially for named EAL pupils. Honest reflection: strategies are still applied by individuals rather than shared as faculty default practice, and impact is not yet systematically evidenced. Priority for 2026–27: build a shared faculty EAL resource bank, agree default adaptations all staff use, and link explicitly to the digital differentiation work in GC2 M1."}}}]},"gc3m2":{"challenge":"Challenge 3: Raising attainment and achievement for all learners","mission":"Mission 2: Increase attainment in Senior Phase","commitments":[{"id":"gc3m2-1","commitment":"Challenge for Top 20% S4–S5 learners.","subject":"Both","lead":"All Staff","successMeasure":"Increase in A/B passes and top-band awards across all subjects.","dataArea":"Whole-school Top 20% data and SQA results analysis identified that, while overall attainment in the faculty is high, the proportion of A and top-band passes was inconsistent across subjects. Drama, Art & Design and Photography each showed different patterns at the top end, with some high-ability pupils not yet converting strong coursework into top-band final outcomes.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Mastery Learning (+5 months), Metacognition and Self-Regulation (+7 months); Education Scotland 'Looking Inwards, Outwards and Forwards' framework; SQA Course Specifications and Understanding Standards. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 3.2 (Raising attainment and achievement) and QI 2.3 (Learning, teaching and assessment).","resources":"Whole-school Top 20% SEEMiS data; faculty meeting time for Top 20% review; In-service Day time on stretch and challenge pedagogy; 1:1 tutorial / coaching time for top-band pupils; external opportunities including competitions, gallery / partner work; DYW links for real-world challenge.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS3.2 / 2.3 – How effectively are we identifying and stretching our Top 20% S4–S5 learners across Art, Drama and Photography? What evidence in coursework, folios and prelim performance shows that 1:1 tutorials and external opportunities are translating into top-band passes?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Top 20% S4–S5 list confirmed against whole-school data; 1:1 tutorial timetable for top-band pupils agreed; external opportunities (competitions, partner work) scoped.","progress":"Top 20% list embedded and shared across the team. First wave of 1:1 tutorials underway, particularly for senior Photography and Higher Drama pupils. External opportunities including competitions and partner work in initial planning."},"t2":{"measure":"Mid-year coursework / folio review for Top 20% pupils; competition entries submitted; gallery / partner engagement underway; prelim preparation for top-band pupils.","progress":"Variable picture by subject. Senior Photography Top 20% pupils responded strongly to studio time and external opportunities. Higher Drama top-end pupils benefiting from 1:1 tutorials, particularly on the written exam (cross-link to Row 2 below). Art & Design Top 20% support more sporadic."},"t3":{"measure":"Folio finalisation; SQA prelim analysis for Top 20%; final external opportunities; targeted exam preparation.","progress":"Continued strength in Photography Top 20% and emerging strength in Higher Drama written work. Art & Design Top 20% remains the inconsistent area — strong individual pupils but no faculty-wide system for routine stretch. External opportunities have been valuable but timing and uptake variable."},"t4":{"measure":"Folios submitted; SQA exams sat; year-end review of Top 20% attainment by subject; planning for sharper, more consistent Top 20% strategy in 2026–27.","progress":"Year-end honest reflection: this strand has been variable by subject. Photography and Higher Drama Top 20% work has clear evidence of impact; Art & Design Top 20% support has not yet been consistent. Carried into 2026–27 with sharper focus — including a unified Top 20% strategy across the three subjects, scheduled 1:1 tutorial calendar, and earlier identification at S4 entry. Awaiting SQA results to confirm impact on top-band passes."}}},{"id":"gc3m2-2","commitment":"Focused improvement of Higher Drama written exam — explicit teaching, timed practice, and peer moderation.","subject":"Drama","lead":"All Staff","successMeasure":"Measurable improvement in Higher Drama written component.","dataArea":"SQA results analysis showed Higher Drama written paper performance consistently below the practical components within the same cohort, with the same pattern visible over multiple sessions. Internal review and SQA verifier feedback confirmed essay structure and depth of analysis as the principal areas where pupils were losing marks. Identified as the single named priority for Drama in the DIP.","research":"EEF Toolkit – Metacognition and Self-Regulation (+7 months), Literacy across the Curriculum (+6 months), Feedback (+6 months); SQA Higher Drama Course Specification and Understanding Standards exemplars; Quigley 'Closing the Reading / Writing Gap'. Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 2.3 (Learning, teaching and assessment) and QI 3.2 (Raising attainment and achievement).","resources":"In-service Day time for explicit essay structure teaching; SQA Understanding Standards event attendance for Higher Drama; 'Looking Outwards' visit / dialogue with another school's Drama department; Pedagogy Pod on writing analysis at Higher level; faculty meeting time for moderation of pupil essays; exemplar bank of past pupil written responses; SQA marker feedback.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 2.3 / 3.2 – How explicitly are we teaching essay structure and analysis for the Higher Drama written paper? What evidence in timed essays, prelim performance and peer moderation shows we are closing the gap between pupils' written and practical performance?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Cohort identified; SQA Understanding Standards attendance booked; 'Looking Outwards' visit to a partner school scheduled; explicit essay teaching sequence designed; baseline timed essay completed for each pupil.","progress":"Baseline timed essays sat by all Higher pupils. Explicit essay structure teaching (introduction, analysis paragraphs, conclusion) underway. Staff attended SQA Understanding Standards events and brought learning back into the classroom. Initial 'Looking Outwards' visit to a partner school completed with clear takeaways on essay teaching practice."},"t2":{"measure":"Second timed essay completed; peer moderation against SQA criteria introduced; mid-year analysis of pupil progress against baseline.","progress":"Pupils visibly more confident in essay structure — introductions and conclusions stronger, paragraph PEEL structure routine. Peer moderation against SQA criteria becoming a regular feature, with pupils developing a sharper sense of what an A/B essay looks like. Analysis depth still developing."},"t3":{"measure":"Prelim Higher Drama written paper sat; full cohort analysis against baseline; targeted intervention for pupils not yet at expected level; SQA Understanding Standards learning applied to final preparation.","progress":"Prelim performance showed measurable improvement on baseline for the majority of pupils, particularly in essay structure. Depth of analysis remains the next development priority — top pupils now writing at A-band level, middle of the cohort improving but inconsistent. 'Looking Outwards' work has clearly shaped final preparation."},"t4":{"measure":"Final timed practice; SQA Higher Drama written exam sat; year-end review of the strand; planning for 2026–27 with refined focus on depth of analysis.","progress":"Strongest evidence-of-impact story in the GC3 attainment work. Explicit essay teaching, timed practice, peer moderation against SQA criteria, SQA Understanding Standards attendance and a 'Looking Outwards' partner visit have visibly improved pupil writing — essay structure now confident across the cohort. Honest reflection: depth of analysis remains the next gap to close. Awaiting SQA results to confirm impact on Higher Drama written component. Strand will continue in 2026–27 with a sharper focus on analysis depth and earlier introduction of essay scaffolds in S4 Nat 5 Drama."}}},{"id":"gc3m2-3","commitment":"Expand senior Art, Drama, and Photography clubs or study support with DYW links to support wider achievement.","subject":"Both","lead":"All Staff","successMeasure":"More pupils achieving ≥5 qualifications including wider achievement options.","dataArea":"SQA results and uptake data showed that pupils achieving ≥5 qualifications were often supported by wider achievement opportunities, and that capacity to extend creative subjects outside lesson time directly supports folio quality and pupil aspiration. Faculty review identified that while individual subject support existed, there was no unified senior phase wider achievement offer or clearly named DYW pipeline.","research":"Education Scotland 'Developing the Young Workforce' (DYW) strategy; Scottish Government's 'Wider Achievement and Skills Framework'; EEF Toolkit – Extending School Time (+3 months) and Aspiration Interventions (mixed evidence – use with care). Aligned with HGIOS4 QI 2.2 (Curriculum), QI 2.7 (Partnerships) and QI 3.2 (Raising attainment and achievement).","resources":"Faculty staff time for after-school folio support and Photography studio access; pupil access to the new Photography studio (cross-link to GC2 M2); DYW coordinator support; potential industry / partner contacts (to be developed in 2026–27); Faculty meeting time to plan the senior wider-achievement offer.","qiQuestions":"HGIOS4 QI 2.2 / 2.7 / 3.2 – How effectively is our senior phase wider-achievement offer supporting pupils to achieve ≥5 qualifications and to articulate their pathway into post-school destinations? How strongly are DYW partnerships embedded in our senior provision?","terms":{"t1":{"measure":"Senior Art folio study support sessions scheduled after school; Photography studio access outside lessons agreed; cohort identified.","progress":"Senior Art folio after-school sessions began running with steady uptake from named senior pupils. Photography studio opened for outside-lesson access as the fit-out progressed. DYW partnerships not yet developed at this stage."},"t2":{"measure":"Continued senior Art and Photography sessions; pupil voice on impact; uptake data tracked.","progress":"Sustained engagement from senior Art and Photography pupils in after-school sessions. Pupil voice strongly positive — pupils cite the extra time as helping folio quality and confidence. Senior Drama coverage running through Romeo and Juliet rehearsal time rather than a formal club structure."},"t3":{"measure":"Continued sessions; pre-exam folio support intensified; wider-achievement options reviewed against pupil pathways.","progress":"Senior Art and Photography wider-achievement provision now an established part of the senior offer. Drama wider-achievement maintained primarily through rehearsal commitment. Honest reflection: DYW formal partnerships and named industry links remain limited this year — work has happened within the school rather than with external partners."},"t4":{"measure":"Year-end review of senior provision and uptake; alignment with whole-school DYW; planning for formal DYW partnerships and a unified senior wider-achievement offer in 2026–27.","progress":"Year-end position: maintained rather than expanded. Senior Art folio study support and Photography studio access are real strengths; Senior Drama wider-achievement happens through performance commitment rather than a formal club. DYW links remain the key gap and the priority for 2026–27 — including named partner contacts, gallery / theatre / industry visitor sessions, and a unified senior wider-achievement offer across Art, Drama and Photography to drive ≥5 qualification rates."}}}]}}};
